{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.62,0.14,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless lump in his left supraclavicular region. He reports increasing fatigue, decreased appetite, and unintentional weight loss over the past few months. He has a medical history of hypertension. His only regular medication is perindopril. He is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history. He lives independently at home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is a firm, non-tender 2 cm lymph node palpable in the left supraclavicular fossa (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following eponymous signs describes this clinical finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pemberton sign","Troisier sign","Kehr sign","Boas sign","Murphy sign"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a left supraclavicular lymph node enlargement along with constitutional symptoms suggesting underlying malignancy. \u003Cstrong\u003ETroisier sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to enlargement of the left supraclavicular lymph node (also known as Virchow\u0027s node), which is highly suspicious for metastatic intra-abdominal malignancy, particularly gastric cancer. The anatomical pathway for this spread is via the thoracic duct, which drains into the left subclavian vein in the left supraclavicular region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPemberton sign\u003C/strong\u003E is elicited by having the patient raise both arms above the head, which in patients with significant mediastinal compression (such as from large goitre) results in facial plethora and venous congestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKehr sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to left shoulder tip pain associated with splenic rupture or other diaphragmatic irritation, due to referred pain via the phrenic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoas sign\u003C/strong\u003E describes right-sided posterior chest wall hyperaesthesia (around T7-T9) associated with acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMurphy sign\u003C/strong\u003E is right upper quadrant tenderness on deep palpation during inspiration, characteristic of acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of Troisier sign, especially when accompanied by constitutional symptoms like weight loss and fatigue in an elderly patient, requires urgent investigation for underlying malignancy, typically with CT imaging of the chest, abdomen and pelvis, and consideration of upper gastrointestinal endoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Troisier sign (enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node) often indicates metastatic intra-abdominal malignancy, particularly gastric cancer.","Constitutional symptoms like fatigue, weight loss, and decreased appetite in elderly patients should raise suspicion for underlying malignancy.","Painless lymphadenopathy in adults over 50 years requires urgent investigation for malignancy."],"references":["Zdilla MJ, Aldawood AM, Plata A, Vos JA, Lambert HW. Troisier sign and Virchow node: the anatomy and pathology of pulmonary adenocarcinoma metastasis to a supraclavicular lymph node. Autops Case Rep. 2019 Feb 25;9(1):e2018053. doi: 10.4322/acr.2018.053. PMID: 30863728; PMCID: PMC6394356."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19401"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19401"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f8b8eee8-db9b-4ae3-9c3e-f8752a00d667.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f8b8eee8-db9b-4ae3-9c3e-f8752a00d667.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":292,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67818"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T19:48:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T19:53:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1100"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82671"}}},"meta":{"canDele